Answer: To sort your list alphabetically, you need to sort your list before passing it to the adapter. You can use the Collections.sort() method to sort your list. You also need to override the compare method in your adapter. Here is how you can do it:

1. In your AsyncTask's doInBackground method, sort your list before passing it to the adapter:

```java
@Override
protected Void doInBackground(Void... params){
    mItem = checkForLauncherIntent(packageManager.getInstalledApplications(PackageManager.GET_META_DATA));
    Collections.sort(mItem, new Comparator<ApplicationInfo>() {
        @Override
        public int compare(ApplicationInfo a1, ApplicationInfo a2) {
            return a1.loadLabel(packageManager).toString().compareTo(a2.loadLabel(packageManager).toString());
        }
    });
    listViewAdapter = new ListViewAdapter(getActivity(), R.layout.list_item, mItem);
    return null;
}
```

2. In your ListViewAdapter, you don't need to override the getView method. The ListView will automatically sort the items when you set the adapter.

```java
public class ListViewAdapter extends ArrayAdapter<ApplicationInfo> {
    private Context context;
    private List<ApplicationInfo> mItem;
    private PackageManager packageManager;

    public ListViewAdapter(Context context, int list_item, List<ApplicationInfo> items) {
        super(context, R.layout.list_item, items);
        this.context = context;
        this.mItem = items;
        packageManager = context.getPackageManager();
    }

    @Override
    public ApplicationInfo getItem(int position) {
        return (null != mItem) ? mItem.get(position) : null;
    }

    public long getItemId(int position){
        return position;
    }
}
```

This should sort your list alphabetically.

Note: The ListView will automatically sort the items when you set the adapter. You don't need to call any sorting method in your ListViewAdapter.

